    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lying Not Necessary</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John Harrington letter comments on July 19 article on people who lie to obtain reservations at Manhattan's trendy and expensive restaurants (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There is a much better way to dine in a popular restaurant without a  reservation.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There is a much better way to dine in a popular restaurant without a  reservation.</p>
        <p>We simply walk in off the street and say: ''Hi. We don't have a reservation.</p>
        <p>Is there any way you could fit us in for dinner tonight?''</p>
        <p>More often than not, there is an available table. And if we need to linger over a preprandial drink at the bar, so much the better.</p>
        <p>To relax and enjoy the crowd is often one of the best parts of the experience.</p>
        <p>NANCY INTRATOR  Mount Kisco, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
